What if I told you there’s a giant, unexplained "bruise" on our universe—a mysterious cold spot so vast and so strange that one of the leading explanations is that we bumped into a parallel universe?

This isn't science fiction; it's one of the biggest puzzles in modern cosmology. Welcome to the podcast that's investigating the CMB Cold Spot, a massive, unusually cold patch in the Cosmic Microwave Background—the faint afterglow of the Big Bang. For years, scientists have debated what could cause such a colossal anomaly. Is it the shadow of the colossal Eridanus Supervoid, a region of space with an eerie absence of matter, playing tricks on light as it travels across the cosmos?

Or is it something far more exotic? We'll dive deep into the mind-bending theories, including the possibility that the Cold Spot is a scar left behind from a collision with a parallel universe. We'll also explore other strange ideas, like a cosmic texture—a type of topological defect in spacetime.
